<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>_x0001_</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Oxfam GB Written Evidence </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Oxfam </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welcomes the opportunity to make this submission to the </span><a name="_Hlk374955135"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Environment,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Food and Rural Affairs Commons Select Committee’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(EFRA) inquiry on food security.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst recognising the focus on the Committee’s inquiry is on UK and EU food security, this submission outlines two policy areas which have implications for both UK and global food security:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The impact of climate change on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> food security</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The world produces enough food to feed everyone, but everyday nearly 900 million people go to bed hungry. Climate change will exacerbate the problem, with the world’s poorest people are already bearing the brunt of its impacts.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Climate cha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nge was a key factor in the Horn of Africa drought</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and in changes in the Sahel</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, directly decreasing harvests and access to food for already vulnerable people, and combined with other factors increasing violent conflict over land and water</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Analysis sugg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ests that climate change could increase the number of people at risk of hunger by 10–20 per cent by 2050, compared to a world with no climate change</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Food price spikes, which can be caused by extreme weather events reducing crop sizes, can be a matter of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> life and death to many people in developing countries, who spend as much as 75 per cent of their incomes on food</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ncreases in global food prices also hit poor people on low incomes in the UK, forcing them to make the choice between heating and eating.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Government must work with other governments to agree a global deal to limit carbon emissions is needed by 2015. High-emitting countries, including the UK, must come to the table with robust commitments in early 2015 in line with what </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">science ind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">icates is needed.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To support low carbon development and sustainable pro-poor energy access, measures are required to shift public and private finance away from climate ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bads</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ such as fossil fuels and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> shift it towards climate ‘goods’ such as renewable ener</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gy and low carbon development that benefits the poorest.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:7.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Climate finance must be mobilised on a large scale to meet those low carbon development needs, and to help poor people, poor farmers and poor co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">untries build resilience and ada</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pt to climate change. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government should push for the agreement of a clear plan from the richest countries on how they will move towards mobilizing the $100bn/year in climate finance by 2020. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Food prices and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">biofuels</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">High and increasingly volatile food prices are having a significant impact on poor families—who in some cases are already spending three-quarters of their income on food. Evidence of the contribution of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biofuel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> policies to rising and increasingly volatile </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">food prices on international markets is so compelling that it led ten international bodies—including the IMF, the World Bank, the FAO and UNCTAD—to recommend in 2011 that G20 governments abolish </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biofuel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> mandates and subsidies.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Oxfam and the Heinrich </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Böll</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Foundation have calculated</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that if Europe were to rule out its support of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biofuels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by 2020, the region could lower its net imports of grain and oilseeds by up to 27 million tons, remarkably reducing its dependence on foreign goods. The global</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prices</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of pl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ant oils would drop by 16 percent. It would also see oilseed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prices</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fall by around 10 percent, with wheat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prices</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also decreasing by about 4 percent.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Following the EU Energy Council’s failure to agree on proposals to reform the EU’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biofuels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> policy, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">K </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government now needs to work hard alongside other member states to ensure a new agreement is reached soon which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">caps food-based </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biofuels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at 5% with a plan for their eventual phasing-out. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Policies to support small</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">holder</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">fa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">mers</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">History shows the import</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ant of public investment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">small-scale agriculture</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in addition to private sector investment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – in particular for women small-scale producers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The two countries that have reduced rural poverty the most in recent decades – China and Vietnam – did so by empo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wering small-scale farmers with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant public support for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> research and development, infrastructure and improving skills, training and access to credit for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rural food producers</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcomed the leadership shown by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government this year in using their Presidency of the G8 for press for action against hunger. However, we believe the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government missed an opportunity to increase public investment in small-scale agriculture.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> There is currently a $213.3bn (£13.7bn) gap </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in poor countries’ agricultural investment plans.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Support to financing mechanisms such as the Global Agriculture and Food Security Program (GAFSP) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">represents one way to achieve this aim. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As part of the budgeted increase to meet the 0.7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ODA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">target, the U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">K Government should commit to spend at least an additional £425 million per year in sustainable small-scale agriculture as their fair share of the amount of investment in agriculture and rural development needed to achieve zero hunger by 2025</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This investm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent could develop much</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needed infrastructure such as feeder roads in rural areas, improve training and credit for small-scale producers, and link farmers to markets.’</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When private investment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is directed to support small-scale farmers and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is done well, it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can act as a catalyst for innovation and job creation, inclusive growth and the protection of our precious </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">environmental resources. In order to benefit the poorest, business models should adhere to some key principles</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">focusing on staple food crops and d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iversified cropping</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">investing in local and regional markets</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">working with producer organisations; investing in processing</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">investing in access to services and focusing R&amp;D on what is appropriate for small-scale producers</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">investing in sustainable agriculture</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.13pt; padding-left:6.87pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">empowering women</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The G8 and other donor countries and developing country governments should prioritise leveraging investment in small-scale farming and small to medium enterprises.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Land rights</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The increase in large scale land acquisitions, fuelled by rising food prices and demand for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biofuels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, is outpacing the ability of national, regional and global governance to keep up. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The acknowledgement of problem of land grabbing by this year’s G8 summit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">declaration was a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welcome step forward. The G8’s plan to establish a number of land transparency partnerships was also welcome, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clarity on their progress to date from DFID is needed. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, the G8 must now go further and show i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t will really get</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to grips with the problem by regulating G8-based companies involved in land deals, and leading more ambitious global efforts to tackle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><a href="http://enoughfoodif.org/issues/land"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">land grabs</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Fraser C Lott, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Nikolaos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Christidis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, and Peter A Stott (2013), “Can the 2011 East African drought be attributed to human-induced climate change?,” Met Office Hadley Centre: Exeter, UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> UN Environment Programme (2011) ‘Livelihood Security: Climate Change, Migration and Conflict in th